<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,150,281]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,415,150,176]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
The two species in this genus are already distinguished by their visual appearance. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Gemineurothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peculiaris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">G. peculiaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more robust, with a much broader head and thorax. The most striking difference, however, concerns their antennae. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2022" box="[297,496,220,246]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Gemineurothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microcephalus">
<emphasis box="[297,496,220,246]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">G. microcephalus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are slender with the median segments much longer than wide and pedicellate, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ulitzka" authorityYear="2022" box="[279,425,255,281]" class="Insecta" family="Rohrthripidae" genus="Gemineurothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peculiaris">
<emphasis box="[279,425,255,281]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">G. peculiaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are short and stout.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
